NEXUS — Revised 3-Minute Demo Script (Student & Consumer-First)
Speaker Roles
Speaker	Role	Owns
S1	The Relatable Voice	Personal hook, emotional close
S2	The Demo Driver	Screen narration, UI walkthrough
S3	The Engineer	Modal pipeline, technical depth
S4	The Live Interactor	Types ticker, reads live inference output
Screen State at Start
Dashboard open. Risk Gauge visible with live MRI number. Narrative table populated.

THE SCRIPT
[0:00 — 0:27] S1 — The Personal Hook

[Screen: Dashboard visible but S1 speaks directly to the audience — no pointing yet]

"You checked your portfolio the morning COVID lockdowns started. Down thirty percent. The news was everywhere — pandemic, supply chains, shutdowns. But your investing app? Just red arrows. Just a chart. No context. No warning. No explanation.

That is not a you problem. That is a missing product.

Every investing app, every algorithm, every trading model reads markets. None of them read the world.

We built the one that does. This is NEXUS."

[0:27 — 1:05] S2 — The Product

[Screen: S2 points to Risk Gauge → scrolls to narrative table]

"NEXUS is a real-time Model Risk Engine. It watches 90-plus live news sources so your financial tools don't have to go blind when the world changes.

(point to gauge)
This is the Model Risk Index — one number that tells you whether markets are behaving like the past or whether something is breaking the pattern. Right now: [READ NUMBER]. We are in a [read: normal / elevated / critical] regime. Below it — momentum. How fast that risk is changing this hour.

(scroll to narrative table)
These are the live narratives NEXUS discovered from today's news — no human labeled any of them. The names you see — [read two aloud] — were written automatically by an AI model running on Modal. Zero manual curation. Fully autonomous."

[1:05 — 1:50] S3 — The Modal Pipeline

[Screen: stays on narrative table — S3 speaks to judges directly]

"Here is the inference architecture — two AI models, both running on Modal.

Every two minutes, our backend scrapes 90 RSS feeds. Every headline hits Stage Two: a sentence transformer — all-MiniLM-L6-v2 — deployed on Modal on an NVIDIA T4 GPU. It encodes each story into a 384-dimensional semantic vector. A mathematical fingerprint of what that story means.

We didn't just call Modal naively. We built a thread-safe batching queue that coalesces up to 32 embedding calls into one GPU round-trip. Thirty-two stories — one network call. That is a 97% reduction in Modal overhead.

When NEXUS finds a story semantically distant from everything it has seen before, it fires Stage Three: a second Modal class — Qwen 2.5, half a billion parameters — with a few-shot financial analyst prompt. That is what writes 'SVB Bank Run Collapse' instead of 'Banking Issue.'

Two Modal classes. One app. Deployed in under two minutes."

[1:50 — 2:30] S4 — The Live Inference Moment

[Screen: S4 types into the ticker search bar]

"Now watch this live.

(types 'NVDA' into search bar — pauses for effect)

That just sent a request to our FastAPI backend, which called our Modal-deployed embedder right now — live GPU inference — to encode 'NVDA' as a semantic vector and compute cosine similarity against every active narrative in our database.

(results appear)

There it is. NVDA's closest narrative is [read top result] — distance [read number]. Whether you hold NVDA in a Robinhood account or you are managing a hedge fund position — that tells you which real-world story is putting pressure on your model right now.

(3D visualization loads)

Three-dimensional vector space — built with Three.js. Every dot is a live narrative. NVDA is here. Closer means more narrative overlap, more model risk. These coordinates come directly from the Modal embeddings produced seconds ago.

Live inference. On screen. Right now."

[2:30 — 3:00] S1 — The Close

[Screen: stays on 3D view]

"That COVID morning when your app went silent — NEXUS would have told you something was wrong before the chart did.

This scales. Individual investors, trading desks, enterprise risk teams — the blind spot is the same at every level.

Right now: 90 sources, two Modal GPU models, live risk scores, updating every two minutes. Not a mockup. Running live.

Next: personal alert thresholds, historical backtesting, and platform integrations.

We are NEXUS."

How the New Hook Improves Impact & Intent Scoring
The original hook opened with SVB and Silicon Valley Bank — a professional finance event. Judges who are students heard "this is for someone else" in the first sentence. That is an Impact & Intent failure. The product's purpose was technically clear but emotionally distant.

The revised hook leads with a moment almost every student in 2020 actually lived. Checking a portfolio during COVID is not a financial expert experience — it is a 19-year-old with a Robinhood account experience. The "that's me" reaction fires within the first two sentences, before any product name is mentioned.

This improves Impact & Intent in three specific ways:

1. User benefit lands before product features. Judges evaluate whether the problem is felt, not just stated. The COVID portfolio moment is felt. "Every algorithm reads markets, none read the world" is the insight that follows naturally — it doesn't need to be explained because the audience has already lived the problem.

2. The user is now unambiguous. The original script implied traders and risk managers. This script says: anyone who has ever checked a portfolio during a news crisis. That is a broader, more credible impact claim and requires no assumed domain knowledge from the judge.

3. The enterprise scalability mention becomes a signal of ambition, not audience narrowing. "This scales — individual investors, trading desks, enterprise risk teams" lands in the close, after judges are already bought in. It reads as upside potential rather than gate-keeping. Judges reward products that start personal and scale up — not products that start institutional and try to reach down.

The technical depth in S3 and S4 is completely preserved. The Modal pipeline, batching queue, Qwen 2.5, and live inference moment are unchanged. The revision only changes the entry point — not the substance.

3 Risks and Adjustments
(unchanged from prior script — still apply)

Risk 1: Judges conflate with news sentiment tools.
Add in S3: "Sentiment tells you if news is positive or negative. We measure semantic distance from model assumptions — that is a different signal."

Risk 2: Modal cold start during live demo.
Run one warm-up query before the room fills. If latency shows, S4 narrates it: "Live GPU call — under two seconds."

Risk 3: Low MRI number looks unimpressive.
Frame it: "Calm regime right now — which is useful information. Models should be trusted. When this spikes, that is your signal to stop trusting them."

Potential Judge Questions and Answers
Q: Who is the actual customer — students or banks?

"The problem is the same at every scale — your tools read charts, not headlines. We built the consumer-accessible version first because it is the fastest way to validate the core signal. The architecture scales directly to enterprise risk desks without any redesign. Same pipeline, higher stakes, larger data volume."

Q: How is this different from news sentiment in existing investing apps?

"Sentiment labels news good or bad. We embed news into vector space and measure how far current events sit from the distribution your model was trained on. Sentiment tells you the mood. We tell you whether the assumptions inside your model still hold. Robinhood showing you 'negative news' is not the same as knowing your NVDA position's quantitative assumptions are under active narrative pressure."

Q: Why would an everyday person care about a 'Model Risk Index'?

"They do not call it that — they call it 'why is my portfolio doing this.' NEXUS answers that question with a number and a reason, not just a chart going down. The MRI is the backend signal; the product surface is just: here is what is driving risk in your holdings right now."

Q: Is this live data or demo data?

"Live. The pipeline scrapes every two minutes. What you see on screen reflects news published in the last two minutes, embedded on a Modal GPU, scored, and pushed to the dashboard. Nothing is staged."

Q: What happens when two narratives conflict — positive and negative signals at once?

"Each narrative is scored independently for surprise and impact. The MRI is a weighted composite. Conflicting signals show up as separate rows in the narrative table with their own trajectories. A trader can see both simultaneously — that tension is itself useful information."